TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Empirical Test of a Stage of Growth Progression Model
AU  - Kazanjian, Robert K.
AU  - Drazin, Robert
Y1  - 1989/12/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.35.12.1489
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.35.12.1489
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1489
EP  - 1503
VL  - 35
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper presents a stage of growth model for technology based new ventures (TBNVs). TBNVs are postulated to evolve through four discrete stages of growth?Conception and Development, Commercialization, Growth, and Stability. Based on a longitudinal sample of 71 ventures in the computer and electronics industries, the hypothesis that TBNVs progress according to this model is tested using the del procedure for prediction analysis of cross-classification tables. The hypotheses are supported, although not all firms progressed as expected. These results suggest that some variation in interstage transition patterns are due to a progression imperative.
AB  - This paper presents a stage of growth model for technology based new ventures (TBNVs). TBNVs are postulated to evolve through four discrete stages of growth?Conception and Development, Commercialization, Growth, and Stability. Based on a longitudinal sample of 71 ventures in the computer and electronics industries, the hypothesis that TBNVs progress according to this model is tested using the del procedure for prediction analysis of cross-classification tables. The hypotheses are supported, although not all firms progressed as expected. These results suggest that some variation in interstage transition patterns are due to a progression imperative.
